  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Few aspects of a Queensland property sale generate more confusion than the holding deposit. A buyer who is keen on the property pays a small sum, often between $1,000 and $5,000, to indicate they are serious. The agent pockets the deposit in the trust account. The seller assumes the property is effectively sold and starts telling family members it is under contract. The buyer assumes they have secured the property and begins organising finance and inspections. A week later, for whatever reason, the buyer decides not to proceed, the agent refunds the deposit, and everyone is back to square one.</p>

      <p>This scenario is common, legal, and entirely preventable with a proper understanding of what a holding deposit actually does. In short: a holding deposit in Queensland does not bind the buyer to buy, does not bind the seller to sell, and does not create a contract of sale. It is a goodwill gesture, nothing more. Sellers who treat it as security for the transaction are setting themselves up for disappointment and, more importantly, are missing the steps that would convert buyer interest into a genuine commitment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a holding deposit actually is</h2>
      <p>A holding deposit is a small payment from a buyer to an agent, intended to demonstrate that the buyer's interest in the property is serious enough to warrant some form of exclusivity while contract terms are being finalised. It is typically paid during the pre-contract phase, after the buyer has inspected the property and expressed verbal interest, but before a contract has been drafted, negotiated, or signed.</p>

      <p>In Queensland, a property sale is not legally effective until a written contract is signed by both parties, typically the REIQ Contract for Houses and Residential Land or the equivalent unit contract. Until that contract exists and is signed by both the seller and the buyer, no amount of money changing hands creates a binding obligation to complete the sale. This is a fundamental feature of Queensland property law, not a technicality, and it applies regardless of what the parties verbally agreed or what the holding deposit was called.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When agents typically use holding deposits</h2>
      <p>Expression-of-interest campaigns are the most common context. In an EOI campaign, the agent invites buyers to submit their best offer by a deadline, the seller reviews the offers, and the seller selects a preferred buyer. A holding deposit taken at the point of selection signals that the buyer is committed to the negotiation and reduces the risk of the buyer walking away while contract terms are being finalised.</p>

      <p>Off-market transactions are another common context. When a buyer approaches a seller directly (typically through an agent who knows both parties), the holding deposit serves to confirm the buyer's interest is real before the seller commits time and energy to negotiating outside of a formal campaign.</p>

      <p>Short negotiation windows are the third common use. If a seller has multiple interested parties and wants to pause further marketing while one buyer negotiates exclusively for a few days, a holding deposit can represent the buyer's commitment to the exclusivity period. Even here, though, the commitment is moral rather than legal: the buyer can still walk at any point before the contract is signed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the deposit is held</h2>
      <p>A holding deposit must be paid into the agent's trust account. Queensland law requires real estate agents to maintain a trust account separate from their operating funds, to keep detailed records of every deposit and withdrawal, and to reconcile the trust account on a regular basis. The agent cannot release the deposit to the seller without the buyer's written consent, and cannot use it to offset commission or any other cost.</p>

      <p>If the sale proceeds to contract, the holding deposit is typically absorbed into the contract deposit (the initial deposit under the signed contract, usually 5% or 10% of the purchase price). If the sale does not proceed, the holding deposit must be refunded to the buyer in full. It cannot be retained as a penalty, cannot be used to compensate the seller for their time or lost opportunity, and cannot be kept even if the buyer has behaved unreasonably. The only circumstance where a holding deposit could be kept is if the buyer and seller had both signed a separate written agreement specifying forfeiture conditions, which is rare and requires careful legal drafting.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The agent's legal obligations</h2>
      <p>Queensland agents have clear obligations when taking holding deposits. They must clearly communicate to the buyer, in writing, that the holding deposit is refundable if the sale does not proceed. They must obtain written acknowledgement from the buyer confirming the buyer understands the holding deposit is not binding on either party. They must not represent the holding deposit as creating any obligation on the seller to accept the buyer's offer, or on the buyer to proceed.</p>

      <p>The Office of Fair Trading can investigate complaints about agents who misrepresent the effect of a holding deposit, either to buyers or to sellers. If a buyer has been told they will lose their holding deposit if they change their mind, or if a seller has been told they are effectively bound to sell because a holding deposit has been received, the agent has misstated the legal position and may face disciplinary action. This is not a grey area.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers should not rely on holding deposits for commitment</h2>
      <p>The central problem with holding deposits, from a seller's perspective, is that they create an illusion of commitment without providing the actual commitment. A buyer who has paid $2,000 into trust can still walk away at any point before contract, for any reason or no reason, and receive the full refund. Their behaviour has no contractual consequence. Your property has been off the market for a week, other buyers have moved on, your agent has stopped running open homes, and you are back to relaunching the campaign.</p>

      <p>This is particularly damaging in fast-moving markets. In Brisbane's inner east, where quality listings can attract multiple interested parties in the first week, taking a property effectively off the market for a holding deposit from a buyer who ultimately does not proceed can cost real money. The buyers who were second and third in the queue move on to other properties; the property re-emerges on the market with a "previously under contract" shadow over it; and the next serious offer may be lower than what you could have achieved with a cleaner campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do instead</h2>
      <p>The answer is simple: move the buyer to a signed contract as quickly as possible. A signed REIQ contract, with the contract deposit in the agent's trust account, creates genuine obligations on both parties (subject to the cooling-off period and standard contract conditions). Once the contract is signed and the cooling-off period has passed without termination, the buyer is committed. Before the contract is signed, nothing you do will make them committed.</p>

      <p>If a buyer offers a holding deposit, the right response is to accept it as a signal of seriousness but to press for a contract immediately. The agent should have the contract drafted and ready to send to the buyer's solicitor within 24 hours. The seller should be prepared to sign quickly once the buyer signs. Holding deposits should be a stepping stone to contract, not a substitute for one. The longer the gap between the holding deposit and the signed contract, the greater the risk the buyer changes their mind.</p>

      <p>Tight timelines on any expression-of-interest process help too. If the EOI window closes on Friday, the contract should be signed by Tuesday at the latest, with finance and inspection conditions running from that point. Sellers who allow a week or more between verbal acceptance and signed contract are giving the buyer time to cool off, find another property, or renegotiate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Treat a holding deposit as a diagnostic signal, not as security. A buyer who offers a holding deposit and then moves quickly to contract is genuinely committed. A buyer who offers a holding deposit and then delays, raises new conditions, or asks for extensions is signalling that their commitment is softer than it appeared. In the second case, the right question is not "how do we hold the buyer to the deposit", because the answer is that you cannot. The right question is "do we continue with this buyer or reopen the campaign", and the answer usually depends on how much time has already been lost.</p>

      <p>Used well, holding deposits are a useful tool for signalling seriousness and pausing a campaign briefly while contract terms are finalised. Used poorly, they are a distraction that gives the seller false confidence and the buyer a free option. A well-structured process around them, with a short fuse to contract and a clear understanding of what the deposit does and does not do, makes them work for sellers rather than against them.</p>

